author: Folegatti 2025
title: Comparative assessment of immunogenicity and safety of recombinant influenza vaccine in children, adolescents, and adults: results from a phase 3, immunobridging, open-label, non-randomised study
domain_ae_include_list: solicited injection site reactions (bruising, induration, swelling, erythema, pain) and solicited systemic reactions (chills, myalgia, malaise, headache, fever) within 7 days post-vaccination , unsolicited systemic adverse events within 30 minutes of vaccination , unsolicited adverse events up to 28 days after vaccination , medically-attended adverse events (MAAEs) up to 28 days after vaccination , serious adverse events (SAEs) throughout the study , and adverse events leading to discontinuation.
setting: multicenter study conducted in 36 centers in the USA and Europe. The European countries included Poland, the Czech Republic, and Spain
population_comment: The study enrolled healthy participants aged 9-49 years. The total number of participants enrolled was 1308, with 1299 receiving the study vaccine. This included 641 participants (49%) in the 9-17 years age group and 658 participants (51%) in the 18-49 years age group. The mean age for the 9-17 years group was 13.0 years (SD 2.5), and for the 18-49 years group, it was 34.3 years (SD 9.2). Overall, 54% of participants were female and 46% were male. Most participants (77%) were White, followed by Black or African American (19%), and 11% identified as Hispanic or Latino.
comments: The study was a phase 3, non-randomised, immunobridging, open-label, uncontrolled, multicenter study conducted in 36 centers in the USA and Europe (Poland, Czech Republic, and Spain) during the 2022-23 northern hemisphere influenza season. It aimed to demonstrate non-inferior immune responses and safety of a quadrivalent recombinant influenza vaccine (RIV4) in participants aged 9-17 years compared with adults aged 18-49 years. The primary outcomes, assessed at day 29, were non-inferiority of immune response by HAI titre ratios and differences in seroconversion rates. The study concluded RIV4 induced non-inferior immune responses and showed a comparable safety profile in the 9-17 years age group versus the 18-49 years age group, with no safety concerns reported. The findings support a potential license extension for RIV to the pediatric population aged 9 years and older.

author: Ahn 2024
title: Epidemiological Characteristics and Outcome of Myocarditis and Pericarditis Temporally Associated With BNT162b2 COVID-19 Vaccine in Adolescents: Korean National Surveillance
date_explain: The government COVID-19 vaccination program targeting adolescents below 19 years of age began on July 19, 2021, and terminated on March 7, 2023. During this period, a total 3,709,063 adolescents aged 12-19 received at least one dose of the BNT162b2 mRNA vaccine, and vaccine-related myocarditis/pericarditis reported until August 2023 were included in this study.
population_comment: adolescents aged 12-19 years old diagnosed with myocarditis/pericarditis that occurred within 42 days of administration with the BNT162b2 mRNA COVID-19 vaccine
ae_outcome1_disagg_text: Median age was 16 years (IQR, 15-18) for mild cases and 17 years (IQR, 16-18) for severe cases. When analyzed by vaccination doses, the rates were 1.30 cases (95% CI, 0.95-1.73) after the first dose, 3.10 (95% CI, 2.50-3.71) after the second dose, and 2.76 (95% CI, 1.90-3.88) after the third dose. The incidence after the second and third doses were significantly higher compared to the first dose (3.10 vs. 1.30, and 2.76 vs. 1.30 cases per 100,000 doses, both P< 0.001). Incidence according to disease severity was 2.02 (95% CI, 1.72-2.35) for mild cases and 0.25 (95% CI, 0.15-0.38) for severe cases per 100,000 doses. The highest incidence was observed in boys after the second dose, with 5.01 (95% CI, 4.12-6.17) cases per 100,000 doses.

comments: AE data - there is AE data on atrial fibrillation (see below)    Also in revax group: 1 case MI after dose 1, 1 case stroke after dose 2, 1 case TIA after dose 3    In RSV 1-dose group: 1 case Bell's palsy       Atrial fibrillation: "As previously reported,2  a numerical imbalance was noted in atrial fibrillation occurring within 30 days postdose 1 (11 [0·09%] RSVPreF3 OA recipients versus 4 [0·03%] placebo recipients, with 8 [0·06%] RSVPreF3   OA recipients versus 1 [0·01%] placebo recipient reporting atrial fibrillation as SAE). The rates of atrial fibrillation reported as SAE within six months post-dose 1 were similar in the RSVPreF3 OA group (15 [0·12%] participants) and the Placebo group (16 [0·13%] participants).  No imbalance in atrial fibrillation was observed within 30 days post-dose 2 (6 [0·12%] participants in RSV_revaccination versus 7 [0·07%] in Placebo, with 2 [0·04%] participants in RSV_revaccination and 3   [0·03%] in Placebo reporting atrial fibrillation as SAE). A numerical imbalance was observed in atrial fibrillation reported as SAE within six months post-dose 2 (11 [0·22%] participants in RSV_revaccination   versus 13 [0·13%] in Placebo).  No imbalance was observed in atrial fibrillation cases occurring within 30 days post-dose 3 (1 [0·07%] participant in RSV_revaccination versus 6 [0·21%] participants in Placebo, all reported as SAE). No imbalance was observed in atrial fibrillation reported as SAE within six months post-dose 3 (4 [0·28%] participants in RSV_revaccination versus 16 [0·56%] participants in Placebo).  The reporting rates of atrial fibrillation were below the expected incidence in the targeted population.  6 The cases occurred in participants with high-risk profiles for onset of atrial fibrillation or in participants with pre-existing conditions. No cases of atrial fibrillation reported as SAE were assessed as related to RSVPreF3 OA vaccination   by the investigator. The Sponsor concluded that the available data do not support a plausible vaccine-related increased risk"

ve_outcome_prime_txt: "Vaccine effectiveness of the adapted COVID- 19 XBB.1.5 vaccines against hospitalisation"    The authors are calling it effectiveness against hospitalization, but the test-negative controls were still hospitalized. The 2x2 table would be A: unvax,SC2+ B: unvax, SC2- C:vax,SC2+ D:vax,SC2-.     The below metrics don't really fit since the outcome was test positivity.

author: Appaneal
title: Early effectiveness of the BNT162b2 KP.2 vaccine against COVID-19 in the US Veterans Affairs Healthcare System
setting: Nationwide study using data from the VA Healthcare System; adult patients >=18 years
population_comment: Authors report differences in SARS-CoV-2 test positivity by age groups, comorbidities, etc, but not VE. Since age and other characteristics  were significant predictors of test positivity, they are adjusted for in the final VE model.
ve_comparator_vax: Did not receive BNT162b2 KP.2 vaccine
ve_timeline: NA- case control study  "Exposed patients received the BNT162b2 KP.2 vaccine at least 14 days before the ARI encounter"
ve_outcome_prime_txt: The authors call this outcome "hospitalization", but it's really VE against SARS-CoV-2 test positivity, amongst all individuals hospitalized for ARIs. Raw data found in Supplemental Table 3.
ve_oc_two_txt: The authors call this outcome "ED/UC visit", but it's really VE against SARS-CoV-2 test positivity, amongst all individuals with ED/UC visits for ARIs. Raw data found in Supplemental Table 4.
ve_oc_three_txt: The authors call this outcome "outpatient visits", but it's really VE against SARS-CoV-2 test positivity, amongst all individuals with outpatient visits for ARIs. Raw data found in Supplemental Table 5.
comments: I have concerns about combining the VE against hospitalization in this study with others in a meta-analysis. Authors are not comparing the effectiveness of the vaccine against hospitalization vs no hospitalization, but rather comparing test positivity amongst all hospitalized individuals. The 2x2 table in this study would be A: vax, sc2+ B: vax, sc2- C: unvax, sc2+ D: unvax, sc2+. All individuals in A-D were hospitalized.

title: Incidence of Respiratory Syncytial Virus in Community-Dwelling Adults Aged 18-64 Years Over 2 Seasons, 2022-2024, in a North American Community
date_explain: October 2022 to April 2023 (season 1) and October 2023 to April 2024 (season 2)
setting: recruited and followed Mayo Clinic primary care patients residing in 4 states: the upper Midwest (Mayo Clinic Rochester and Mayo Clinic Health System in MN and WI), the Mayo Clinic in Florida, and the Mayo Clinic in Arizona
population_comment: Disaggregated by 18-49, 50-59, 60-64
epi_geo_rsv: 4 states: the upper Midwest (Mayo Clinic Rochester and Mayo Clinic Health System in MN and WI), the Mayo Clinic in Florida, and the Mayo Clinic in Arizona
epi_incidence_rsv: In season 2, the RSV-ARI and RSV-LRTD incidence rates were 26.39 (95% CI, 21.73-31.75) per 1000 person-years (1.51% attack rate) and 12.43 (95% CI, 9.31-16.26) per 1000 person-years (0.72% attack rate). RSV-ARI incidence peaked in November 2022 and December 2023.
epi_hospitalization_rsv: For the first season, 1 (0.9%) hospitalization without intensive care unit admission. For season 2, 1 (0.9%) hospitalization without intensive care unit admission.
epi_medical_rsv: For the first season, 18 (16.1%) participants with RSV-ARI were medically attended within 30 days of follow-up. For season 2, there were 34 (30.4%) medically attended participants: health care utilization for RSV-ARI.
epi_ifr_rsv: For both seasons, there were no deaths in participants with RSV-ARI (data not shown).
epi_other_rsv: For season 2, there were several notable differences. We found higher incidence rates with increasing age, noting overlapping 95% CIs. Those residing in an urban setting had higher incidence rates when compared with a rural setting. Participants with a CCI of 0 had a lower incidence rate of RSV-LRTD as compared with a CCI ≥1, despite overlapping 95% CIs.

Although we observed inferior immunogenicity of concomitant  administration in terms of seroconversion rates for the ancestral  SARS-CoV-2 strain, the similar postvaccination antibody titers  against SARS-CoV-2 (both WT and Omicron BA.5 subvariant) and  influenza strains (A/H1N1, A/H3N2, and B/Yamagata), and the  tolerable safety profile indicate that a co-administration strategy  would be feasible."

All documented respiratory tract symptoms with PCR-confirmed RSV positivity were adjudicated to be either ARD, LRTD (severe, with 3-symptoms, or with 2-symptoms) or no endpoint by an independent adjudication committee."
ve_oc_two_txt: "LRTD with at least 3 or at least 2 of the following symptoms: new wheezing or worsening of pre-existing wheezing, new shortness of breath or worsening of pre-existing shortness of breath, new cough or worsening of pre-existing cough, new sputum production or worsening of pre-existing sputum productions, signs of severe LRTD. ve_oc_three_txt: "RSV-associated ARD was defined by the presence of either 1 ARD symptom lasting for at least 24 h or 2 simultaneously occurring ARD symptoms (irrespective of duration), with onset at least 14 days following vaccination until the end of one RSV season, with RSV- association confirmed by PCR. ARD symptoms included: rhinorrhea, nasal congestion, pharyngitis, earache, new cough or worsening of pre- existing cough, new wheezing or worsening of pre-existing wheezing, new sputum production or worsening of pre-existing sputum production, new shortness of breath or worsening of pre-existing shortness of breath, fever >100 ◦ F / > 37.8 ◦ C (oral temperature)."
ve_oc_four_txt: severe LRTD, i.e. the presence of at least 1 of the following signs: hypoxemia (oxygen saturation < 92 % at rest in conjunction with an at least 3 % decrease from baseline), respiratory rate > 25 breaths/Min, imaging evidence of new onset of bronchitis, bronchiolitis, or pneumonia
comments: -No VE estimated for severe disease  -Authors also performed an "exploratory analysis of VE" based on number and intensity of self-reported symptoms, but I did not include those numbers (in supplemental) since they were not primary or secondary outcomes  - a few serious AEs reported, but none from our list; fatal events determined to be unrelated to vaccine by study investigator  -Vax not US-licensed

second_review_comment: Study should be excluded

author: Küçükerdem
title: Evaluation of menstrual irregularities following COVID-19 infection or vaccination: The impact of COVID anxiety and associated risk factors
comments: - Authors don't differentiate between COVID-19 infection and COVID-19 vaccination for menstrual irregularities  - Authors present p-values in the text but I can't find the corresponding numbers in the data tables
exclude_reason: I think this study should be excluded based on quality. There's a random sentence in the methods stating "efforts were made to obtain a minimum of 384 animals per treatment group"...but this is a cross-sectional survey study?    Authors also present data in the text that I can't find in the data tables. They also don't differentiate between COVID vax and infection. Because this was cross-sectional without any calculations based on time since vaccination, menstrual irregularities could be inappropriately attributed to a vaccine given over a year ago. The authors didn't actually find any significant differences based on vaccine receipt, so this likely won't make much of a difference anyway.

From table 1:  Definite VITT:  All five of the following criteria:  • Onset of symptoms 5-30 days after vaccination against SARS-CoV-2 (or ≤42 days in patients with isolated deep vein thrombosis or pulmonary  embolism  • Presence of thrombosis  • Thrombocytopenia (platelet count <150 x 10%/L)  • D-dimer level >4000 FEU  • Positive anti-PF4 antibodies on ELISA    Probable VITT:  D-dimer level >4000 FEU but one criterion not met (timing, thrombosis, thrombocytopenia, or anti-PF4 antibodies) or d-dimer level unknown or 2000-4000  FEU and all other criteria met    Possible VITT:  D-dimer level unknown or 2000-4000 FEU with one other criterion not met, or two other criteria not met (timing, thrombosis, thrombocytopenia, or anti-  PF4 antibodies)    Unlikely VITT:  Platelet count < 150 × 10%L without thrombosis with D-dimer level <2000 FEU, or thrombosis with platelet count >150 × 10%/L and D-dimer level <2000  FEU, regardless of anti-PF4 antibody result, and an alternative diagnosis that is more likely.

author: Jeong 2025
title: Global estimates of vaccine-associated narcolepsy from 1967 to 2023
comments: mRNA vaccine is included as disaggregated. Influenza vaccines is all types from the 60s to 2023. Not sure if this should be excluded based on study type but leaving for second reviewer opinion. - Derek    In case it's useful, here's the aggregate flu vaccine data:   Influenza vaccines showed the highest signal for association with narcolepsy out of all vaccines studied. Overall Risk Signal: The reported odds ratio for all influenza vaccines combined was 156.53 (95% CI, 147.62-165.97). Subgroup Analysis: The signal was particularly high for the Pandemrix vaccine (ROR 852.31) but was also significant for non-Pandemrix influenza vaccines (ROR 122.67).  Highest-Risk Population: For influenza vaccines, the strongest signal was observed in individuals aged 12 to 17 years. Time to Onset: The mean time to onset following influenza vaccination was 146 days.  Influenza vaccines showed the strongest disproportionality for narcolepsy: ROR 156.53 (95% CI 147.62-165.97) overall and 112.19 (105.32-119.51) in health-professional-only reports.

author: Silverman 2025
title: Influenza-Associated Acute Necrotizing Encephalopathy in US Children
setting: In January to February 2025, we initiated a nationwide call for cases by contacting 76 US pediatric neurology programs and simultaneously by making announcements through several academic societies (Child Neurology Society, American Academy of Neurology, Pediatric Neurocritical Care Research Group, and American Academy of Pediatrics Section on Critical Care). Thereafter, various public health agencies (state public health departments, Emerging Infections Network, Program for Monitoring Emerging Diseases, and CDC) implemented calls for cases
population_comment: This study was a multicenter case series of children diagnosed with ANE with longitudinal follow-up
epi_other_flu: This is a multicenter case series describing 41 US children with influenza-associated acute necrotizing encephalopathy (IA-ANE) from the 2023-2025 flu seasons. The study reports high morbidity and mortality: 27% of patients died, and among the 27 survivors with 90-day follow-up, 63% had moderate to severe disability. A key finding was that among the 38 patients with available vaccination history, only 6 (16%) had received the seasonal influenza vaccine.

author: Omole
title: A phase 3 randomized, double-blind clinical study to evaluate the safety and immunogenicity of V116 when administered concomitantly with influenza vaccine in adults 50 years of age or older
domain_ae_include_list: erythema, pain, swelling, fatigue, headache, myalgia, deaths
population_comment: >=50 years of age
coadmin_vax2_type: Concomitant administration of flu vaccine and V116
coadmin_outcome_other: "Statistical criteria were prespecified to demonstrate the noninferiority of V116 immunogenicity when administered concomitantly with QIV compared to sequential administration. V116 administered concomitantly with QIV met the noninferiority criterion to V116 administered sequentially with QIV for 20 of 21 serotypes contained in V116, and QIV administered concomitantly with V116 met the noninferiority criterion to QIV administered sequentially with V116 for 3 of 4 strains contained in QIV. In the 2 endpoints where noninferiority cutoffs were missed, they were missed by a narrow margin. For V116, serotype 23B missed the noninferiority cutoff for OPA but the IgG GMC following vaccination in the concomitant group (4.24 μg/ml) supports that an immune response to serotype 23B was induced. In addition, supporting data evaluating the proportion of participants with a ≥4-fold rise in OPA GMTs from pre- to postvaccination with V116, and the proportion of participants with ≥1:40 HAI titers after QIV, demonstrated robust immune responses were induced to all components of both vaccines."
coadmin_vax2_type_2: Sequential administration of flu vaccine and V116
comments: Authors concluded that concomitantly administered flu and V116 vaccines was noninferior to sequential administration, but a few non-inferiority criteria were missed. I chose the "same/noninferior" option on the coadministration page since that's what the authors said, but this should probably be interpreted with caution!
